# migrations/

Forward-only SQL migrations for `db.migrate: versioned` mode. Ignored
while the yaml says `migrate: auto` (dev default: gorm AutoMigrate
from `db.WithTables`).

Workflow:

    chok migrate create add_notes_index   # scaffolds NNNN_add_notes_index.sql
    # edit the SQL, commit it — main.go embeds this directory
    chok migrate up --config chok.yaml    # or let the app apply on start
    chok migrate status --check --config chok.yaml

Applied files are SHA-256 audited (CRLF and LF hash identically). A dirty
attempt fails startup until an operator inspects the actual schema and runs
one version-scoped repair action with the ledger checksum and a reason:

    chok migrate repair retry <version> --checksum <sha256> --reason "..."
    chok migrate repair mark-applied <version> --checksum <sha256> --reason "..."
    chok migrate repair accept-drift <version> --checksum <sha256> --reason "..."

On MySQL, never choose retry until every implicitly committed DDL effect has
been inspected and the database has been restored to the pre-migration state.

There are no down migrations: correcting a mistake means shipping the
next forward migration. chok's own battery tables (users, identities,
audit_logs, casbin_rule, schema_migrations) stay AutoMigrate-managed
and are listed by `chok migrate status` as the framework whitelist.
